Welcome to the=C2=A0636=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since Monday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0143,137 smart,=
 curious folks by subscribing here:=20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Thursday!=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s been a ton of talk =E2=80=93 in ecommerce, media, SaaS, and=
 web3 =E2=80=93 about the importance of community. There are far fewer actu=
al examples of building community-first in a way that translates into real =
metrics. Glossier comes to mind as a good example of a similar idea, conten=
t-to-commerce, and many companies build strong communities within their cus=
tomer bases, but starting with the community is rare.=C2=A0
The idea of starting with a community and then building products and servic=
es specifically for them is one I=E2=80=99ve been obsessed with for a while=
=2E When I was thinking about launching N=
ot Boring Club pre-COVID, I wrote a =
memo-to-self in Notion on just this topic:=C2=A0
If I=E2=80=99m being honest, the target customer I was thinking of for Not =
Boring Club would have been too diffuse to pull off a community-first busin=
ess really well. They=E2=80=99d have too many different needs, and not enou=
gh of the same ones.=C2=A0
But the idea stuck with me, and when I met Bravado=E2=80=99s Sahil Mansuri,=
 I knew I=E2=80=99d found someone doing it right. Today, we=E2=80=99re goin=
g to dive into Bravado=E2=80=99s playbook. It hasn=E2=80=99t been easy to g=
o community-first, but the effort is beginning to pay off spectacularly, an=
d I expect it to compound for a long time to come.
This post is a Sponsored Deep Dive. I always say that I only write about co=
mpanies that I=E2=80=99d invest in, and fortunately, we were able to invest=
 in Bravado out of Not Boring Capital. You can read more about how I choose=
 which companies to work with on Sponsored Deep Dives here [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/bced8ac6-a5be-4c1b-9ff6-df165a314c2a?r=3D9p0gt ].
This is the last essay I=E2=80=99m writing until September, although we hav=
e some incredible guest posts lined up. Enjoy the rest of your summer!=C2=
=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The ABCs of Bravado
ABC. Always Be Closing.=C2=A0
Partially thanks to Glenngary, Glen Ross, partially thanks to those calls a=
nd emails you get, and partially thanks to cringe posts on LinkedIn, sales =
has developed a cartoonish reputation.=C2=A0
While sales is a great way to make a lot of money, and the best path for no=
n-technical people to get into tech, it=E2=80=99s not a career that most pe=
ople dream of, the way they dream of becoming engineers or product managers=
 or designers or founders.=C2=A0
Sahil Mansuri [ https://substack.com/redirect/4049490c-3a00-4577-a0ff-fa8d2=
f7ca874?r=3D9p0gt ], the founder and CEO of Bravado [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/fb073e36-4c89-4eb1-9543-4a335eb50561?r=3D9p0gt ], wants to change =
that. =E2=80=9CI LOVE sales. I want to turn sales into a profession that pe=
ople aspire to,=E2=80=9D he told me when we met over Zoom for his Series B =
pitch in February. Bravado=E2=80=99s homepage captures its founder=E2=80=99=
s enthusiasm:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CSales is the best job in the world.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Sahil=E2=80=99s enthusiasm for sales is infectious, and his pitch worked. N=
ot Boring Capital invested in Bravado=E2=80=99s Series B, a $26 million rou=
nd led by Tiger with participation from Redpoint, Freestyle Capital, Flow V=
entures, Precursor Ventures, Mark Pincus, and my friends Lenny Rachitsky [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/017528e2-9a9d-4cd8-a884-c9f409bc6510?r=3D9p0g=
t ] and Sahil Bloom [ https://substack.com/redirect/02a8ef46-4e1d-4ba8-90c2=
-237b73aa237b?r=3D9p0gt ].=C2=A0=C2=A0
When Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/db869af9-b100-4cb4-8977-477964b=
d0da5?r=3D9p0gt ] CEO John Andrew Entwistle [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/31e4b05b-8693-4aac-90e1-5b3daffd56cd?r=3D9p0gt ] offered to introduce me t=
o Sahil, I was a little skeptical =E2=80=93 another sales platform? I wasn=
=E2=80=99t sure it answered the =E2=80=9CSo what?=E2=80=9D question I ask w=
hen I=E2=80=99m considering an investment, or that sales software counted a=
s a hard startup [ https://substack.com/redirect/13f73e79-beb3-4d34-bd0d-69=
4ea0f36adc?r=3D9p0gt ]. But I trust JAE and there were a bunch of things to=
 love about the company and the industry it=E2=80=99s tackling:=C2=A0
Industry: Sales is the #1 most popular role in the country, and B2B Sales i=
s the 3rd fastest-growing
Grit: Sahil started Bravado five years ago, and they=E2=80=99ve had a produ=
ct in-market for 3.5 years, but they didn=E2=80=99t start monetizing until =
last year.=C2=A0
Growth: Bravado scaled from $0 to $4 million in ARR in 9 months when it lau=
nched its Jobs product with Sahil as, ironically, the company=E2=80=99s onl=
y salesperson
It all clicked, though, when Sahil laid out the approach Bravado=E2=80=99s =
taken to get to where it is, and the optionality that gives the company in =
the future. It=E2=80=99s that approach that we=E2=80=99re going to dive int=
o today: community-first distribution.=C2=A0
In The Good Thing About Hard Things, I wrote that =E2=80=9CHard startups on=
 the bits side are solving difficult technical challenges, creating new bus=
iness models, or touching industries that previously didn=E2=80=99t make se=
nse to touch.=E2=80=9D
While community-first isn=E2=80=99t a brand new business model =E2=80=93 ev=
ery company and DAO talks about building community-first =E2=80=93 Bravado =
has executed on that playbook brilliantly, building a community for years b=
efore monetizing it effectively, in a way that I haven=E2=80=99t seen befor=
e.=C2=A0
Sahil calls it =E2=80=9Creverse engineering a SaaS company.=E2=80=9D Instea=
d of building software for salespeople and then bolting on a community of c=
ustomers, a brand, conferences, and the like, Sahil started by building a f=
ree professional network for salespeople, like =E2=80=9CStackOverflow for S=
ales=E2=80=9D: one place where salespeople can go to get better at their jo=
bs.
It was a slog, and after three years in the trenches, the community didn=E2=
=80=99t really take off until last year, when the company decided to make i=
ts message boards pseudonymous so that, unlike LinkedIn, =E2=80=9Cpeople ca=
n ask for real advice without bloviating.=E2=80=9D With that one shift, Bra=
vado=E2=80=99s free product, the War Room, took off. Today, Bravado has ove=
r 250,000 salespeople in its network, representing 50,000 companies. And th=
ose 250k people had to go through some friction to get there; I went throug=
h the signup process, and it=E2=80=99s a meaty eleven steps, including conn=
ecting LinkedIn to verify your responses.=C2=A0
That traction is a clear sign that Bravado fills a hole in the market for s=
alespeople who want to get better at their jobs by learning from a communit=
y of top sellers. . Out of over 4,000 accredited universities in the US, on=
ly 50 have a major or minor in sales. There=E2=80=99s no Dribbble or Figma =
for salespeople, like there is for designers. Salespeople have made do on L=
inkedIn, but there=E2=80=99s gotta be a better way to get tips and advice, =
and to just celebrate a win, than doing it in view of your whole profession=
al network.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the hole War Room fills, but War Room is just the first step=
 in a brilliant strategy to build products for the community that Bravado h=
as so patiently built. The reason Sahil built Bravado in the first place wa=
s to build better products for salespeople after realizing that all of the =
existing ones =E2=80=9Care awful.=E2=80=9D But in a market dominated by a g=
iant like Salesforce, he knew he couldn=E2=80=99t just build a product and =
try to sell it the same way all of the would-be Salesforce-killers have tri=
ed.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The community-first strategy has paid off handsomely for Bravado. Thanks to=
 War Room, when Bravado turned on its first paid product, Jobs, it grew to =
$4 million in revenue in 9 months at a $4 blended Customer Acquisition Cost=
 (CAC) with 95% organic growth. When the hiring market recently turned sour=
, it listened to its members in the War Room, built off of the Jobs product=
 foundation, and quickly launched Flex. Flex, which lets sales professional=
s work as Freelancers, opens up new options for the future of Bravado, for =
who gets hired, and how salespeople leverage themselves.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s what building community-first enables: optionality. With the=
 War Room humming, Bravado=E2=80=99s just getting started on its quest to b=
uild better products for salespeople. In the process, it=E2=80=99s rewritin=
g the playbook for bottoms-up, community-first go to market. I think that i=
ntegrating this deeply with the community will become table stakes for new =
SaaS startups that want to build deep moats going forward.
Today, we=E2=80=99ll dive in to understand the ABCs of the community-first =
juggernaut Bravado is building, and where it might go in the future:=C2=A0
Sahil=E2=80=99s Sales Story=C2=A0
Meet Bravado: The Anti-SaaS SaaS Company
From ABCs to JOBs
Bear Market Flex=C2=A0
The Future of Sales
To understand where Bravado=E2=80=99s headed, you need to understand how Sa=
hil got to Bravado.=C2=A0
Sahil=E2=80=99s Sales Story
In May, Sahil joined me on Not Boring Founders to talk sales. In response t=
o my first question, =E2=80=9CWhat will the world look like in a decade if =
you=E2=80=99re wildly successful in your mission?=E2=80=9D, he said:=C2=A0
When kids are growing up, someone wants to be an astronaut. Someone wants t=
o be a firefighter. These days, I think a lot of people want to be a tech f=
ounder or an engineer. I don't know a single kid that grows up and is like,=
 man, one day, I hope I get to be a salesperson, you know? No, one's got th=
eir little GI Salesperson Jane character that they're running around with.=
=C2=A0
His mission is to change that, to build a world in which:=C2=A0
People aspire to be in sales.
Sales is recognized as an amazing way for non-technical people to break int=
o tech.
Sales is taught in high school and college as a skill that you need in orde=
r to be successful.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a mission that comes from personal experience. Growing up, Sah=
il said, =E2=80=9CI was good at math, I was good at tinkering, I took every=
 AP physics, chem, etc=E2=80=A6.=E2=80=9D He was smart, but he had no idea =
what he wanted to do. But while he was in college in Washington, DC, he did=
 what people in DC do: got involved in politics. Specifically, he joined th=
e Obama Campaign in Field Operations.=C2=A0
Field Operations is essentially sales. Going door-to-door explaining your c=
andidate=E2=80=99s position, hosting events to get people excited, and lots=
 and lots of cold calling. And Sahil loved it. He had found his calling.=C2=
=A0
After school, Sahil joined Meltwater, a 600 person sales organization, as a=
 Sales Manager, and quickly became the #1 sales representative in the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s 10-year history. Within two years, he was promoted to Managing=
 Director and sold to companies like Exxon, Prudential, Pernod Ricard, AIG,=
 Panera Bread, and the Air Force.=C2=A0
He left Meltwater in 2011 to become the 23rd employee at a little startup c=
alled Glassdoor [ https://substack.com/redirect/3b41ab4b-2d61-46d9-9f71-157=
7e4b7b6c5?r=3D9p0gt ] as an Enterprise Sales Manager. Selling to companies =
like Google, Facebook, Microsoft, and Amazon, he was the #1 rep out of 50 i=
n his first year with the company.=C2=A0
Moving on up, Sahil got hired as the VP of Sales at a smaller startup calle=
d Virool, and there, he became the largest customer of a tiny Israeli compa=
ny, SalesPredict, building a predictive AI lead scoring tool. The product w=
asn=E2=80=99t intuitive for the user, and when Sahil gave feedback to the S=
alesPredict team, they asked him to join them and fix it himself.
In his time in sales, Sahil had realized two things about sales software:
All sales tools are awful.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s no bottoms-up sales tooling.
He wanted to understand why that was, so he took the job and joined SalesPr=
edict to help build its product. Working with designers, engineers, and dat=
a scientists, he needed to brush up on his technical skills, so he started =
learning R. When he got stuck on an issue, he turned to his now co-founder =
Yoni Acriche to ask for help, and Yoni replied, =E2=80=9COh, just Google it=
=2E=E2=80=9D
So he copy-pasted the code he was having trouble with into Google, and voil=
a=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
The exact issue popped up in Stack Overflow [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/db0551d7-776d-49cc-ab11-b25056a019d4?r=3D9p0gt ], the =E2=80=9Cpublic plat=
form building the definitive collection of coding questions & answers,=E2=
=80=9D with dozens of helpful answers.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhy doesn=E2=80=99t something like this exist in sales?=E2=80=9D h=
e wondered.=C2=A0
Then, when he was interviewing a designer, she sent him a link to her portf=
olio in Dribbble [ https://substack.com/redirect/7643493c-b49a-4e3d-ad5e-88=
1b0e01da16?r=3D9p0gt ], the community where creatives share their work.=C2=
=A0
Once again, he wondered, =E2=80=9CWhy doesn=E2=80=99t something like this e=
xist for sales?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The question kept coming back up as he played with the delightful software =
that non-salespeople got to use, right when the =E2=80=9Cconsumerization of=
 enterprise software [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ea44a6f-0eb3-4847-b23=
5-52ac3f5ae48e?r=3D9p0gt ]=E2=80=9D was in full swing, and became increasin=
gly intent on bringing the same level of software to sales. Finally, in the=
 summer of 2016, eBay acquired SalesPredict for $40 million [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/7af4f244-1ac1-44b5-b8b3-81c6226748ab?r=3D9p0gt ], and Sahi=
l decided it was time to scratch the itch.=C2=A0=C2=A0
But having spent so much time in sales at early-stage startups, Sahil knew =
what a grind it was getting even really good software in customers=E2=80=99=
 hands via the traditional enterprise sales model, so he set out to flip th=
e script.
Meet Bravado: The Anti-SaaS SaaS Company
Product-led, or bottoms-up, growth has become a popular approach to custome=
r acquisition for consumerized software startups. Give away a free version =
of software that a handful of employees love to use, make it really easy fo=
r them to sign up for pro features with a credit card, and then layer on sa=
les using those early adopters as a beachhead for the company-wide deal. Pr=
oduct-led growth has propelled companies like Dropbox, Zoom, Figma, Notion,=
 Slack and many more to great heights.=C2=A0
That motion is standard in most enterprise SaaS verticals, but it hasn=E2=
=80=99t really hit sales. Quick: think of a sales tool that people love so =
much that they beg their management teams to buy it for the company. I can=
=E2=80=99t either. More often, at some point, after trying some spreadsheet=
s, then graduating to a lightweight CRM, the VP Sales convinces the CEO: it=
=E2=80=99s time. Salesforce.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve done this before,=E2=80=9D they say. =E2=80=9CIt will=
 be easy,=E2=80=9D they say. =E2=80=9CThree months, tops!=E2=80=9D they pro=
mise.=C2=A0
And then, inevitably and invariably, six months later, the VP Sales is brea=
thing down the engineering team=E2=80=99s neck and keeping the Sales Ops pe=
rson in the office late every night =E2=80=9Cuntil we get this damn thing i=
mplemented.=E2=80=9D They finally do. It=E2=80=99s not perfect, but it work=
s. Leadership finally has a good pulse on the company=E2=80=99s pipeline. T=
hey understand the funnel, and realize that there=E2=80=99s a big leak betw=
een =E2=80=9CMQL=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CClosed-Won.=E2=80=9D They re-jigger =
the flow; SDRs are now to call MQLs twice, email twice, and then call a thi=
rd time. The sales team, of course, doesn=E2=80=99t love this new system. T=
heir boss is on them for not making enough calls. Every night, after they=
=E2=80=99re done doing their real job, they sit there and update Salesforce=
 because those automatic integrations they were promised are broken and the=
 engineering team is focused on customer-facing work and they=E2=80=99ll fi=
x it in a few months. The company misses revenue targets. The VP Sales is f=
ired (VP Sales, incidentally, have the shortest tenure of any executive pos=
ition at 19 months [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3b860b5-99a6-47ef-956c-=
307696c421b8?r=3D9p0gt ]). The new Chief Revenue Officer (she has 25 years =
experience, she=E2=80=99s not settling for =E2=80=9CVP Sales=E2=80=9D) come=
s in and says she can turn it around, no problem, =E2=80=9CWe just need to =
set up our Salesforce the right way so I=E2=80=99m properly instrumented.=
=E2=80=9D And on it goes.=C2=A0
Whew. Where was I?=C2=A0
Right, for some reason, bottoms-up software hasn=E2=80=99t taken off in sal=
es like it has in other verticals, so companies end up buying clunky, hard-=
to-implement old software. While =E2=80=9CNo one ever got fired for buying =
Salesforce=E2=80=9D certainly isn=E2=80=99t true in the long-run, it sounds=
 right in the short-term.=C2=A0
Given his decade-plus in sales, Sahil knew that he wasn=E2=80=99t going to =
win the sales tools category with a traditional enterprise sales approach, =
or even with a bottoms-up approach. =E2=80=9CThe push to the first few mill=
ion in ARR is really hard and expensive,=E2=80=9D he explained, =E2=80=9Cun=
til you build a brand, get reviews, write case studies, earn trust, host co=
nferences, and build momentum.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Instead, Sahil decided to take a different tact. He calls Bravado an =E2=80=
=9CAnti-SaaS SaaS Company.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s an inverted approach: star=
t by building a community of sales professionals, listen to what they need,=
 build products to fill those needs, get feedback from the community, and i=
terate.
By building community-first, Bravado was building a brand, getting access t=
o a pool of customer insights, and actually developing its own distributed =
sales team for its eventual products.=C2=A0
Think of it this way. Software companies typically generate high margins by=
 building products with high fixed costs (typically R&D) and low marginal c=
osts (it costs practically nothing to make copies of the software). Build o=
nce, sell millions of times, profit. Of course, there are still marginal cu=
stomer acquisition costs =E2=80=93 it takes some amount of money to convinc=
e each customer to use or buy the product. What Bravado is doing has a simi=
lar logic. It spent high upfront costs building a community of its target c=
ustomers, and now, it should be able to distribute new products to them and=
 through them at low marginal customer acquisition costs.
So Bravado started simple, with a community for salespeople.=C2=A0
People joined, but growth was slow. Bravado experimented with new formats. =
In one iteration, it let sales leaders start their own communities, like #L=
ive-Better-Sell-Better and #Other-Side-of-Sales and invite members. At the =
time, all profiles on Bravado were attached to real people with their real =
names, and Sahil told me that while people were finding value, there was st=
ill a lot of LinkedIn-esque posturing.=C2=A0
To learn how Bravado caught lightning in a bottle, and how it turned commun=
ity-first into real revenue in 7 months=E2=80=A6=20
If you=E2=80=99re interested in learning more about Bravado, including the =
new Flex product for companies to hire salespeople on a 100% commission bas=
is, or generally want to nerd out about how to grow revenue during the down=
turn, you can reach Sahil directly at sahil.mansuri@bravado.co.
Thanks to Sahil for working with me, and to Dan for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today, we=E2=80=99ll see you tomorrow morning for a =
Weekly Dose of Optimism!
Thanks for reading,=20
